ng from his capital शोणितपुर; pleased शिव by praise; was a devotee of शिव; and became the head of the गणस्; in return for his services, the Lord शिव guard- ed his city; {{F}}1:  भा. VI. १८. १७-18; X. ६२. 2; ८८. १६; Br. III. 5. ४२-4; ७३. १०१; IV, २९. १२३; M. 6. १०, १३; वा. ६७. ८३; Vi. I. २१. 2; V. 1. २४.{{/F}} took part in the देवासुर war between Bali and Indra; fought with सूर्य and was helped by his ९९ brothers; a friend of Kamsa and जरासन्ध; he welcomed जरासन्- dha, and offered to help him and sent his two ministers and a vast army with जरासन्ध. {{F}}2:  भा. VIII. १०. १९, ३०; X. 2. 2; ३६. ३६; [५१ (v) 1-१८].{{/F}} Once addressed शिव that he found no use for his thousand arms for there was none to fight him, and even the elephants at the quarters ran away in fear of him; शिव replied that soon there would be some- body equal to him who would put down his pride of power. {{F}}3:  Ib. X. ६२. 2-११.{{/F}} The marriage of his daughter उषा was the cause of a battle between शिव and कृष्ण; the guards of the harem once reported to बाण that they suspected the presence of some male in उषा's palace; soon he found Aniruddha there and imprisoned him to the distress of his daughter; was attacked by सत्यकी when शोणितपुर was besieged by the वृष्णिस्; found his army scattered and rushed towards कृष्ण leaving [page२-476+ ३१] सत्यकी, when his charioteer and horses were killed; कोटरा his mother appeared before कृष्ण naked and with dis- hevelled hair, while बाण entered his city; once again attacked कृष्ण who chopped off his arms when शिव praised कृष्ण as ब्राह्मण and pleaded for his devotee, बाण, being left with his four arms remaining; deprived of all except two on account of Aniruddha; release of Aniruddha. {{F}}4:  Ib. X. ६२. 1 २८-35; ६३. 8, १७-21 ३०-49; ६१. २३ (9); III. 3. ११; XI. १२. 5. Vi. V. ३२. 7-8; ३३. 1-५०.{{/F}} Capital Tripura. The gods appealed to Rudra and in the meantime नारद made बाण's wives leave the path of strict chastity and prepared the way for the Asuras' ruin. Rudra put the city to flames; appealing with a लिन्ग on his head, he was blessed. Attained मोक्ष by सत्सङ्ग; {{F}}5:  M. Chh. १८७-188.{{/F}} killed by कृष्ण. {{F}}6:  वा. ९८. १०२.{{/F}}(II)--a son of Danu and महासेन. M. 6. २०; २४५. १२.--शिव gan2as. Br. III. ४१. २७.--ruled for १००० years; as kings of Maga- dha; the last of them was रिपुञ्जय. भा. IX. २२. ४९; Vi. IV. २३. १२-13.--a division of the night. वा. ६६. ४४.--of बृहस्पति; {{F}}1:  वा. ७९. ५९.{{/F}} those learned in, fit for श्राद्ध. {{F}}2:  Br. III. १५. ३२.{{/F}}(I)--a son of अनुह्राद and सुर्म्या; disciple of पैऌअ; learnt the ऋग् Veda and taught it to Bodhya and others; rearranged the सम्हितास् into four parts with the help of his four disciples, Bodhya, अग्निमाढक, याज्ञ- valkya and पराशर; arranged three more सम्हितास् and entrusted them to कालायनि, गार्ग्य, and कथा japa, all his pupils. भा. VI. १८. १६; XII. 6. ५४-5; Vi. III. 4. १६-18, २५.(II)--the father of Jambha and three others. Br. III. 5. ३९.(III)--a son of प्रह्लाद. M. 6. 9; Vi. I. २१. 1.(IV)--the son of Virocana; father of four sons. वा. ६७. ७६, ७९. [page२-480+ ३३]--of कौशिक gotra. Br. III. ६६. ७२; वा. ९१. १००.(I)--a son of बाष्कल; author of the वालखिल्य। सम्हिता; imparted it to बालायनि and others. भा. XII. 6. ५९.(II)--an Angirasa and a मन्त्रकृत्; a श्रुतऋषि; a pupil of पैऌअ in charge of the ऋग् Veda; he arranged it into four सम्हितास्; his disciples were Bodhya, अग्निमाठर, पराशर and याज्ञवल्क्य. Br. II. ३२. १०७; ३३. 4, १३; ३४. २५; M. १९६. १२; वा. ५९. ९८; ६०. २५-26; ६१. 2.(III)--(भरद्वाज) a pupil of Satyasuja author of three सम्हितास् which were imparted to his dis- ciples आपनाप and others; {{F}}1:  Br. II. ३४. ३२; ३५. 5.{{/F}} a शाख Pravartaka. {{F}}2:  वा. ६०. २९.{{/F}}(I)--a son of Arjuna and उलूपि, the daughter of the king of मणिपुर; became a पुत्रिकापुत्र. भा. IX. २२. ३२; Vi. IV. २०. ५०.--a disciple of शौनक; {{F}}1:  वा. ६१. ५३.{{/F}} of कौशिकगोत्र. {{F}}2:  Ib. ९१. ९९.{{/F}}--काश्यप gotraka1ras. M. १९९. 7.(I)--one of the two sons of Druhyu and father of Setu (Ripu-ब्र्। प्।) भा. IX. २३. १४; Br. III. ७४. 7; वा. ९९. 7; Vi. IV. १७. 1-2.(II)--a son of रोमपाद; (लोमपाद-ब्र्। प्।) and father of कृति. भा. IX. २४. 2; Br. III. ७०. ३८; Vi. IV. १२. ३९.(III)--a disciple of शुनक (शौनक-ब्र्। प्।, वि। प्।) who taught him a सम्हिता. भा. XII. 7. 3; Br. II. ३५. ६०; Vi. III, 6. १२. [page२-458+ २८](IV)--a son of देववृध and गान्धिनी; the best among men; righteous and truthful; a महारथ of the सात्वतस्; through his precept and that of his father, several thousands attained immortality; {{F}}1:  भा. IX. २४. 9-११; वा. ९६. १५; Vi. IV. १३. 3-6, १०७; M. ४४. ५६-60.{{/F}} performed sacrifices and lavished gifts; got the jewel Syamantaka and gave it to कृष्ण, to be returned by the latter. {{F}}2:  Br. III. ७१. १३, ८१-2, ९६ and ९८.{{/F}}(V)--a son of सम्पाति. M. 6. ३५.(VI)--is अक्रूर. वा. ९६. ५६.--of कौशिक gotra. Br. III. ६६. ७१.(II)--a commander of भण्ड. Br. IV. २१. ८५.--आश्रम at, sacred to Nara-नारायण in Gan- धमादन; the place where Hari is said to perform तपस् for the welfare of the world; visited by कृष्ण; as directed by कृष्ण on the eve of his departure to Heaven, Uddhava made it his abode; {{F}}1:  भा. III. 4. 4, २२, ३२; VII. ११. 6; X. ६६[13]; XI. 4. 7; २९. ४१, ४७; XII. 9. 7; Br. III. २५. ६७; Vi. V. ३७. ३४.{{/F}} Kakudmi spent the evening of his life at that place. {{F}}2:  भा. IX. 3. ३६{{/F}} See बद्रिका. Here Mucukunda performed तपस् meditating on Hari. {{F}}3:  Ib. X. ५२. 4.{{/F}} See बदरियाश्रम. A तीर्थ sacred to ऊर्वशी; {{F}}4:  M. १३. ४९.{{/F}} sacred to the पितृस्; {{F}}5:  Ib. २२. ७३.{{/F}} आश्रम where Mitra and वरुण performed penance. {{F}}6:  Ib. २०१. २४.{{/F}}--the name of the द्वीप where बादरायण was born. M. १४. १६.--see Badari; {{F}}1:  भा. X. ५२. 4.{{/F}} in the the ब्रह्मरन्ध्र of the personified Veda. {{F}}2:  वा. १०४. ७८.{{/F}} [page२-456+ २६]--the sages of, visited द्वारका. भा. X. ९०. २८[5].--a wife of the Sun god; mother of the अश्विन्स्. भा. VIII. १३. 9, १०.hence called so. वा. १०२. ७६.--a Mt. which entered the sea for