्डीश अवतार् of the Lord. वा. २३. २११.--one of the seven Maruts; {{F}}1:  Br. II. २२. ३९; M. १६३. ३२.{{/F}} the kind of wind that helps Brahmaja clouds to rain: the chief of the second वातस्कन्ध; {{F}}2:  Br. II. २३. ९८; III. 5. ८३; वा. ६७. ११५.{{/F}} the clouds controlling जीमूत clouds. {{F}}3:  Ib. ५१. ३६.{{/F}}--a sage of the Auttama epoch. M. 9. १४.--the top hill of Gomanta. Pursued by जरासन्ध, राम and कृष्ण fled to this. Besieged by जरासन्ध. भा. X. [५३ (v) 5]; ५२. १०-11 [3], [१६].--one of Danu's sons. वा. ६८. 7.(I)--a son of प्राचीनवत्, and father of Namasyu (Manasyu वि। प्।). भा. IX. २०. 2; Vi. IV. १९. 1. [page२-430+ २५](II)--a son of विन्ध्यशक्ति and a great hero: capital at कान्चनक: performed the वाजपेय and other यज्ञस्, father of four sons: ruled for 6 years. Br. III. ७४. १८४-6; वा. ९९. ३७१-2.(III)--a son of उपदानवी. M. ४९. १०.(IV)--a son of Trasyu. वा. ९९. १३३.(V)--a king of the dynasty of विन्ध्यशक्ति. Vi. IV. २४. ५६.--a ruler of किलिकिला. भा. XII. 1. ३३.--a tribe; {{F}}1:  M. ११४. ४५.{{/F}} an eastern Janapada. {{F}}2:  वा. ४५. १२३.{{/F}}--at the time of creation men full of रजस् attain the भूतस् and इन्द्रियस् through the favour of gods; by the meditation of the Lord the three गुणस् get their respective गुणस् defined; all of common धर्मस् attain विकार for creation; happiness and misery, धर्म and अधर्म, truth and untruth reach each according to his inclination; separation of गुणस्। वा. १०३. २५-33.(I)--a तीर्थ sacred to Hari. Sages of this place visited द्वारका; was visited by बलराम; {{F}}1:  भा. VII. १४. ३०; X. ९०. २८ [3]; XII. 1. ३७; X. ७९. १०; M. २२. 8.{{/F}} capital of [page२-427+ ४२] the Aila पुरूरवस् on the north bank of the यमुना. {{F}}2:  Br. III. १३. १००; ६६. २१; IV. ४४. ९८; वा. ९१. ५०.{{/F}} ललिता enshrined at; {{F}}3:  M. १३. २६.{{/F}} fit for श्राद्ध; {{F}}4:  वा. ७७. ९२.{{/F}} occupied by the Kurus, {{F}}5:  Ib. ९९. २१५.{{/F}} represents the nose of the personified Veda; {{F}}6:  Ib. १०४. ७६; १०६. ६९.{{/F}} a Janapada of the Gupta emperors. {{F}}7:  Ib. ९९. ३८३; Vi. IV. २४. ६३; VI. 8. २९.{{/F}}(II)--(माहात्म्यम्): मर्कण्डेय to युधिष्ठिर on; here is प्रजापतिक्षेत्र; people who bathe here go to heaven and who die here are liberated from सम्सार; guarded by Indra; there are five deep channels in प्रयागा with the Ganges flowing in their midst. Sins are washed off by entering its boundary. The goddess यमुना, the daughter of the Sun God is ever present: It is a place haunted by the Gods, Asuras, ऋषिस् and Siddhas; {{F}}1:  M. ch. १०४.{{/F}} one who remembers प्रयागा from his own native home or from a foreign place on the eve of his death goes to the world of ब्रह्मा. Leaving the heaven, he is reborn as a King of जम्बूद्वीप; gifts of cows, jewels and gold here attain great merit: The giver is born in Uttara Kuru regions and enjoys long life. {{F}}2:  Ib. ch. १०५.{{/F}} One should not drive to the place in a conveyance drawn by bullocks lest the virtue of bathing should be lost. Giving daughters in mar- riage, and death near the अक्षयवट helps one in going to the world of शिव. One should go and do charities with utmost faith. Here are ६० crores and १०००० holy spots; well- known for a शिव shrine: प्रतिष्ठान lies to the east of the Ganges, and to its north lies the Hamsaprapatana तीर्थ। There are again ऊर्वशीरमण, Sandhya वट, कोटी तीर्थ, and others, all holy; {{F}}3:  Ib. ch. १०६.{{/F}} by merely listening to the greatness of प्रयागा a man gets liberated. To the south of प्रयागा there is a ऋणमोचन तीर्थ where by residing for a night and by bathing, one never runs into debts. A pilgrimage to P. gives the benefit of an अश्वमेध sacrifice: relieves his मनेस् for ten generations: its circumference is five yojanas [page२-428+ ३५] and every step is sacred: the greatness of the यमुना described; {{F}}4:  Ib. chh. १०७-8.{{/F}} a man dying at P. gets the benefits of a Yogin: the king of all तीर्थस्: P. is again the place where both Kambala and अश्वतर reside. It is the altar of प्रजा- pati. It is more sacred, being situated on the banks of the Ganges. It is the giver of heaven, the personification of bliss and truth: Reading the महात्म्य takes one to heaven; {{F}}5:  Ib. chh. १०९-110.{{/F}} Here ब्रह्मा, विष्णु and शिव are all present. ब्रह्मा stands on the Northern part of the तीर्थ to protect it: विष्णु is represented as वेणी Ma1dhava, while शिव is present in the shape of a banyan tree. In addition to them, the gods, oceans and mountains also live there. It is known as प्रजापति Indraks2etra. One who remembers this every day attains heaven. After hearing this, युधिष्ठिर is said to have bathed in प्रयागा. {{F}}6:  Ib. chh. १११-112; १८०. ५६; १९२. ११; १९३. १९.{{/F}}--a यामदेव. Br. II. १३. ९२.--a Mauneya Gandharva. Br. III. 7. 2.--death pollution for ten days for Brah- manas, १२ for क्षत्रियस्, १५ for वैश्यस् and one month for शूद्रस्. Vi. III. १३. १८-19.--is शिव: he who finds his abode among the graves. वा. ३०. १४१.--funeral rites described. Vi. III. १३. 7-१६.--in गया. वा. १०९. १५.--the world of the dead. वा. ११०. ४४.--in गया. वा. ८३. २०; ११०. 8 and 9. [page२-450+ ३०]--महालय lasting for fifteen days. वा. ८३. ४१.--is Yama: once he asked a certain merchant to take all his wealth and spend (5/6) of it at गया for श्राद्ध in his name; and (1/6) for himself for doing the Karma; so he did and the Preta got released from the bondage of सम्सार। वा. ११२. १५-20; Vi. V. २३. ४४.--spirits harassing children. भा. II. 6. ४३; १०. ३८; VI. 8. २५; X. 6. २७; ६३. ११; XI. १०. २८.--a part of the शिला at गया where पिण्ड is offered to the dead; here is प्रेतकुण्ड; {{F}}1:  वा. १०८. १५, ६७.{{/F}} here Pretas receive offering; on the head of गया. {{F}}2:  Ib. ११०. ६६.{{/F}}--a mind-born mother. M. १७९. १९.--a चरकाध्वर्यु. Br. II. ३३. १३. [page२-449+ ३०](I)--a कला of the moon. Br. IV. ३५. ९२.(II)--a कला of विष्णु. Br. IV. ३५. ९५.(I)--a wife of the God of Love, the other being Rati; was in her previous birth a courtesan, Anangavati who observed विभूतिद्वादशीव्रतम्। M. १००. ३२.(II)--a daughter of दक्ष and wife of Pulastya; {{F}}1:  वा. १०. २७, ३१; २८. २२; Vi. I. 7. २५.{{/F}} mother of three sons, दानाग्नि, देवबाहु and Atri; {{F}}2:  Br. II. 9. ५२, ५५; ११. २६.{{/F}} also son Dattoli (वि। प्।). {{F}}3:  Vi. I. १०. 9.{{/F}}(III)--a wife of Angirasa. Vi. I. 7. 7.--a vow in honour of Hari. M. १०१. 6.--a daughter of दक्ष. वा. 1. १२२.--a मुद्रादेवी. Br. IV. ४४. ११४.--a son of तामस Manu. Br. II. ३६. ४९; वा. ६२. ४३.--a name of ललिता; मन्त्रिनी. Br. IV. १७. ३४, ४३; ३१. १०५.--a Brahmana belonging to the अजमीढ family. भा. IX. २१. २१.--an Apsaras. वा. ६९. 4.--a Bhavya god. Br. II. ३६. ७२.(I)--one of the two sons of स्वायम्भुव Manu and an अम्श of Vasudeva; {{F}}1:  भा. III. १२. ५५; २१. 2; IV. 1. 9; XI. 2. १५; IV. 8. 7; M. 4. ३४; वा. ३३. 6; ५७. ५७; Vi. I. 7. १८.{{/F}} married two wives Bar- हिष्मती daughter of विश्वकर्मन् and another; had ten sons and a daughter through his first wife; among whom were two sons आग्निध्र and Manu Uttama; through the second wife he had three sons, all rulers of Manvantaras; though a भागवत and devoted to नारद, in obedience to his father's wishes remained a house-holder and administered his king- dom; three of the ten sons by the first wife महावीर, Kavi and Savana remained bachelors all through life; ruled for eleven अर्बुद years; possessed superhuman powers; he fol- lowed the sun by making seven circuits, determined to make night also day; these seven circuits resulted in the formation of seven seas and seven continents of which his sons became rulers; gave his daughter to उशनस्; following the foot- steps of नारद he classified the land fixing rivers, moun- tains and forests as boundaries; {{F}}2:  भा. V. 1. (whole); १६. 2; VIII. 1. २३; XI. 2. १५;{{/F}} founder of a glorious line; his descendents; {{F}}3:  Ib. V. 6. १४; ch. १५ (whole).{{/F}} obliged to विष्णु; {{F}}4:  Ib. IV. २१. २८; ३१. २६; Br. II. १४. 6; २९. ६३; ३०. ३९; ३६. ६५; Vi. III. 1. २४-5.{{/F}} went to heaven by तपस्। {{F}}5:  M. १४३. ३८; Vi. I. ११. 1.{{/F}} Married the daughter of Kardama and had two [page२-448+ २४] daughters, सम्रात् and कुक्षी besides ten sons; to this line belong the Manus, स्वारोचिष, Uttama, तामस and Raivata. {{F}}6:  Ib. II. 1. 3-6.{{/F}}(II)--a son of शतरूपा. Br. I. 1. ५७; वा. ६२. ५९.(III)--a son of वैराज Manu; {{F}}1:  Br. II. 9. ४१; वा. 1. ६६; १०. १६.{{/F}} married काम्या; {{F}}2:  Ib. २८. २८.{{/F}} had ten sons and two daughters. {{F}}3:  Br. II. ११. ३३.{{/F}}(IV)--a god of the आद्या group. Br. II. ३६. 69(V)--heard the विष्णु पुराण from ऋभु and narrated it to भागुरि. Vi. VI. 8. ४३.--the dynasties of Priyavrata; स्वारो- चिष, Uttama, तामस, and Raivata Manus. वा. ६२. ५६.--Indra of the XI epoch of Manu. Vi. III. 2. ३०. [page२-389+ ३४]--one of the seven seers of the स्वारोचिष epoch. Vi. III. 1. ११.--a mixture of ghee and curds as a sacrificial offering. Br. IV. 1. ९८; वा. १००. १०३.--a son of शिबि. Vi. IV. १८. १०.(I)--A son of विरूप, and father of Rathi- tara; {{F}}1:  भा. IX. 6. 1; Br. III. ६३. 6; वा. ८८. 6; Vi. IV. 2. 8-9.{{/F}} a मन्त्रकृत्. {{F}}2:  M. १४५. १०३.{{/F}}(II)--the son of पृथु and father of आन्ध्र; {{F}}1:  वा. ८८. २६.{{/F}} a मन्त्रकृत् and of the Angirasa branch. {{F}}2:  Ib. ६९. १००.{{/F}}(III)--the son of अनरण्य and father of हर्यश्व. Vi. IV. 3. १८.(I)--a son of Vaivasvata Manu. Being appointed by his teacher to be in charge of cattle he attend- ed to it zealously. During nights he kept awake in वीरासन posture. On a dark rainy night a tiger entered the stall and caught hold of a cow, when the other cows ran pell-mell. At this the prince drew the sword, and in the darkness he cut off the head of a cow and the ear of the tiger. Next morning he reported the sad news to the preceptor, who cursed him to become a शूद्र. He however continued to live a life of celibacy, and detachment to things mundane, ever con- templating on Hari. He reached ब्रह्मा by entering the forest-fire in the course of his wanderings. भा. VIII. १३. 3; IX. 1. १२; 2. 3-१४; Br. III. ६०. 3; M. ११. ४१; १२. २५; वा. ६४. ३०; ८६. 1; Vi. III. 1. ३४; IV. 1. 7, १७. [page२-390+ २८](II)--a son of स्वायम्भुव Manu; {{F}}1:  Br. II. ३८. ३१; वा. ८५. 4; ८६. 1.{{/F}} killed his preceptor Cyavana's cow and was cursed to become a शूद्र. {{F}}2:  Br. III. ६१. 1.{{/F}}--the last son of Somaka अजमीढ and father of Drupada. भा. IX. २२. 2; वा. ९९. १९२; Vi. IV. १९. ७३.--the son of माध्रि's son, युधाजित्; had two sons श्वफल्क and Citraka. वा. ९६. १०१.--a manifestation of Hari born of पृश्नि and Sutapas during the श्वायम्भुव epoch. भा. X. 3. ४१.(I)--the wife of सविता, and mother of शावित्री, व्याहृती and others. भा. VI. १८. 1.(II)--देवकी in the epoch of स्वायम्भुव Manu: Married Sutapas the progenitor: was engag- ed in तपस् with her husband for १२००० divine years. To them was born Hari by name पृश्निगर्भ. भा. X. 3. ३२-41; 6. २५.--a class of gods doing श्राद्ध. Br. III. १०. १०९; वा. ७३. ६१.--a god of Sumedhasa group. Br. II. ३६. ५९.--one of the ten branches of the सुकर्माण clan of Devas. Br. IV. 1. ८८; वा. १००. ९२.--a daughter of मरीचि and सम्भूति. वा. २८. 9.--a son of Raucya Manu. वा. १००. १०९.--a वीरमात; surname of कुन्ती (s.v.). A sister of Vasudeva. Became the adopted daughter of the child- less Kuntibhoja who was a friend of her father, शूर. She pleased दुर्वास by service and obtained some मन्त्रस्; just to test their efficacy, she invoked the Sun-God who was before her. She requested him to return. But he con- ferred on her a son, when she was yet a maiden, and went away. Afraid of scandals, she abandoned the child in the river and later became the wife of पाण्डु; {{F}}1:  भा. I. 8. 3, १७, ४४; १३. 3; १५. ३३; III. 1. ३९-40; IX. २४. ३०-36; X. ४९. 1; ५८. 7; ७१. ३९; Br. III. ७१. १५०-51; Vi. IV. १४. ३१-4.{{/F}} gave birth to three famous sons, all devaputras and equal to Indra. युधिष्ठिर from Dharma, भीम from मारुत, and Arjuna from Indra. {{F}}2:  M. ४६. 4, 7-9; वा. ९६. १४९-153; ९९. २४३; Vi. IV. १४. ३५-6.{{/F}}(II)--various essences extracted from, by differ- ent classes of beings, following पृथु's example; {{F}}1:  भा. IV. १८. १३-27.{{/F}} also [page२-381+ ३८] धरा; first milked by ब्रह्मा; in the Vaivasvata epoch, Prthu milked her. {{F}}2:  Br. II. २०. 1-4; २१. १२; ३७. 3, १२-20; III. 3. ३४; 5. ७९; IV. 2. ११ and १८.{{/F}}(I)--adopted as daughter by the first king पृथु; mother of all creatures, of different janapadas, cities, castes, mountains, rivers, etc.; {{F}}1:  M. १०. 1, ३५; वा. ४२. ७८-81; ५०. 2-4; ६३. 3-4. ७४. ३०.{{/F}} ५० (१००(1/2) crores-म्। प्।) crores of yojanas in extent; its बाधविस्तार begins with योजनाग्र which is one crore in every direction from Meru in the middle; three crores of yojanas in all the four direc- tions; the inside circumference of the earth; the पर्यास equal to the extent of the नक्षत्र मण्डलम्; {{F}}2:  Ib. १२४. १२; वा. ५०. ६८-75.{{/F}} comprising seven islands and being tributary to the sons of स्वायम्- bhuva Manu. {{F}}3:  M. १६६. 6; २५८. ११. वा. ३३. 4-5.{{/F}}--otherwise known as Lokapadma of which Meru forms the tendril; from this lotus came the four- faced ब्रह्मा; the earth, lotus shaped. वा. ३४. ३७, ४४; ४१. ८६.(I)--(Vainya) the son got out of Vena by the churning of his right arm by the sages to save him from falling into hell: is considered the ninth incarnation of Hari. The first king who introduced agriculture. {{F}}1:  भा. II. 7. 9; III. 1. २२; IV. १३. २०; I. 3. १४; M. 4. ४४; 8. 2-१२; वा. ६२. १२६-182; ch. ६३; Vi. I. १३. ३९.{{/F}} Pane- gyrised by the Gandharvas, and Siddhas playing on different musical instruments. For his coronation, presents came from Indra, ब्रह्मा, Yama, Rudra and other gods; praised by सूत, मागध and Bandin. Though these were dis- couraged, yet they continued to praise him for his righteous administrative policy. His sway extended to the Udaya hills. {{F}}2:  भा. IV. chh. १५-16 (whole).{{/F}} Due to scarcity of supply, people complained of hunger, when पृथु aimed his arrow and threatened to vanquish her. The earth let herself be milked. With स्वा- yambhuva Manu for the calf and his own palms as pail; he milked the essence of all plants. This was followed by the sages, gods, asuras and others. Hilly tracts were levelled, and different kinds of villages, cities and towns were orga- nised for the first time. {{F}}3:  Ib. IV. chh. १७-18 (whole) Vi. I. १३. 9, ४०-43.{{/F}} Consecrated himself to perform one hundred अश्वमे- dhas on the सरस्वती. When ९९ were over, jealous Indra ran away with the sacrificial horse. Advised by Atri, the king's son pursued him as the kite did रावण and recover- ing the animal, earned the title विजिताश्व. Again Indra stole the horse, and विजिताश्व pursued him and recovered it. पृथु saw marks of sin on the part of Indra behaving like [page२-382+ ४२] a miscreant and aimed his arrow at him. Persuaded by ब्रह्मा, he controlled his rage and became friendly to Indra. On advice from विष्णु, he cast off his enmity to Indra and embraced him. Asked of the Lord to be ever devoted to him. {{F}}4:  Ib. IV. १९ (whole); २०. 1-३१.{{/F}} On his return to the capital, the citizens accorded him a welcome. Made the middle country between गन्गा and यमुना his home. Advised his subjects, who praised him, to conduct themselves righteously. Was visited by सनत्कुमार with three other sages who taught him आत्मग्ञान। {{F}}5:  Ib. IV. २०. ३८; २१ (whole); २२. 1-४८.{{/F}} His queen Arcis gave birth to five sons, all rising to his ideal. He followed the path of the लोकपालस्, and his fame as of सोमराज reached the ears of women as that of राम the ears of the virtuous. {{F}}6:  Ib. IV. २२. ५३- ६३.{{/F}} Finding himself aged, he entrusted the kingdom to his sons and left with his queen to the forest. Launched on a course of severe penance until his last breath went out of his body. In the funeral pyre which the queen lighted for her husband's cremation, she threw her- self and ascended to heaven, praised by the wives of the gods. {{F}}7:  Ib. IV. २३ (whole).{{/F}} Thus पृथु, the lord of seven द्वीपस्, still thirsting to have more territory, renounced his kingdom and sought refuge with Hari. {{F}}8:  Ib. VIII. १९. २३; XII. 3. 9; X. ६०. ४१.{{/F}} A मन्त्रकृत् of the चाक्षुस Manu line. The first क्षत्रिय to be a राज. By him the earth became known as पृथ्वि. {{F}}9:  Br. II. ३६. ८३.{{/F}} His accession was the occasion of a प्रतिसर्ग when rulers were appointed over several classes of beings; got the grace of विष्णु and milked the cow-earth, got grains and eatables and made the earth flow with milk and honey; there was no need for the application of the अर्थशास्त्र maxims; he levelled the ground from Cape Comorin to the हिमालयस् and cleared the forests; {{F}}१०:  M. १०. १०-35.{{/F}} made it safe and secure; made the १६ gifts. {{F}}११:  Ib. २७४. १२.{{/F}} [page२-383+ २९](II)--a son of तामस Manu; {{F}}1:  भा. VIII. 1. २७; वा. ६२. ४१-71; Vi. III. 1. १८.{{/F}} a कश्यप and a मन्त्रकृत्. {{F}}2:  Br. II. ३६. ४७; M. 9. १५; १४५. १००; वा. ५९. ९७.{{/F}}(III)--the son of Anenas and father of Visva- randhi (विश्वगन्धि ?). (विष्टराश्व-वि। प्।). भा. IX. 6. २०; Br. III. ६३. २६; Vi. IV. 2. ३५.(IV)--a son of Rucaka. भा. IX. २३. ३५.(V)--a son of Citraratha, of the वृष्णि tribe; sta- tioned by कृष्ण to defend the northern gate of मथुरा; was on the right detachment of कृष्ण's army; got killed in the Yadava contest at प्रभास. {{F}}2:  Vi. V; ३७. ४६.{{/F}} ^1 भा. IX. २४. १८; X. ५०. २० [3]; [५० (v) १२].(VI)--the son of अनीनस् and father of पृष- दश्व. वा. ८८. २५.(VII)--the son of Vibhu. Br. II. १४. ६७. वा. ३३. ५७.(VIII)--a son of Supratika the elephant. Br. III. 7. ३४१.(IX)--a son of शिवदत्त. Br. III. ३५. १२.(X)--a son of Citraka. Br. III. ७१. ११४; वा. ९६. ११३; Vi. IV. १४. ११.(XI)--a son of Suyodhana. M. १२. २९. [page२-384+ २५](XII)--a son of अश्विनी and अक्रूर. M. ४५. ३२.(XIII)--a son of पार. M. ४९. ५५.(XIV)--a son of पुरुजानु. M. ५०. 2.(XV)--the सूत sprang from the sacrifice of; {{F}}1:  वा. 1. ३३-4.{{/F}}a मन्त्रकृत्. {{F}}2:  Ib. ५९. ९७.{{/F}}(XVI)--Father of Antardhi (अन्तर्धान) and वादि. वा. ७०. २१; Vi. I. १३. ९३; १४. 1; २२. 1.(XVII)--the son of Vibhu. Vi. II. 1. ३८.(XVIII)--a son of परावृत्. Vi. IV. १२. ११.(XIX)