ith पृथु; {{F}}1:  Br. II. ३६. १९७; III. ५०. 9; ५६. २४; ६३. १६५; ६९. ४०; IV. ३८. ४४; Vi. I. 6. १८-19; V. ३६. 6; वा. ३४. १०; ४८. 7.{{/F}} its evacuation by the people for the woods during periods of anarchy. {{F}}2:  M. 6. १३, १०. ३२; ४७. २५७; १४३. 3.{{/F}} [page२-348+ ४५](I)--Indra of the Vaivasvata epoch; १००० eyed. भा. VIII. १३. 4; IX. 8. 8; X. ७७. ३६-7; XII. 8. १५. Br. II. ३६. २०५. वा. ३४. ७५; ६२. १७८; ६४. 7; ६७. १०२. Vi. III. 1. ३१ and ४३; V. २१. १६.(II)--Indra observed आदित्यशयनम्; {{F}}1:  M. ५५. ३२; १७८. ६५; २४६. ६९; २४८. १४.{{/F}} one of the authors on architecture; {{F}}2:  Ib. २५२. 2.{{/F}} the abode of. {{F}}3:  Ib. २७४. ७८.{{/F}}--a Northern tribe. M. ११४. ४०.(I)--a King of extensive learning, had a friend whose name and behaviour were not known; went in search of a suitable place for the realisation of various pleasures; this he found in a city of nine entrances resembling [page२-345+ ३८] भोगवती on the southern side of the हिमालयस्. By accident he met a charming lady protected by a serpent and followed by a number of ladies and men; moved by her charms he requested her to be his wife and she agreed; For a hundred years they continued to enjoy pleasures; पुरञ्जन used to visit the kingdoms, विभ्राजित, Saurabha, दक्षिण and Uttara पाञ्चालस्, ग्रामक, वैशस and others through the different entrances of the city guarded by the Superintendent; influenced by her charms he came com- pletely under her control; mad with desire for hunting, once he left his queen and went to the forest and after killing many a game, he returned home and desired to meet the queen whom he found lying on the bare ground in misery; he consoled her and once more yielded to her love and influence at the cost of his youth; he had ११०० sons and ११० daughters for whom he found worthy wives and suitable bridegrooms; he was then engaged in animal sacri- fices, when the followers of चण्डवेग, a Gandharva, attack- ed the city of पुरञ्जन and the Superintendent defended it single-handed for १०० years. This placed the citizens and the kinsmen in misery. A daughter of काल, once in the company of पूरु went to Bhaya, the Lord of the Yavanas to marry him; he adopted her as his sister; with her and his brother प्रज्वार he set out to wander in the world; in his tour the Yavanas attack- ed the city of पुरञ्जन; प्रज्वार burnt it down; पुरञ्- jana was seized and taken to the Yavana camp; the sacrificial animals tore him to pieces; was born as the daughter of Vidarbha राजसिम्ह; married by Malayadhvaja पाण्ड्य and gave birth to a daughter and seven sons, all kings of the द्राविड country. When the पाण्ड्य left for penance she went with him and served him; she wailed at his death; and when about to give up her own life, a Brahmana who called himself her friend consoled her by saying that he and she were once the two Hamsas of मानस and that she took to a household life and underwent all miseries; instructed thus she recollected her old status and remained calm; {{F}}1:  भा. IV. chh. २५-28 (whole).{{/F}} an allegory [page२-346+ ३४] for जीव and परमात्मन्; पाञ्चालस् are the five senses while the nine entrances to the city refer to the nine द्वारस् of the body; sometimes the जीव is a male sometimes a female, and sometimes God, and sometimes man or beast in accordance with Karma. {{F}}2:  Ib. IV. २९. 2-9, २९.{{/F}}(II)--an Asura having his city in the third talam. Br. II. २०. २७.--the wife of पुरञ्जन; a charming woman protected by a serpent with five hoods and followed by ten servants each in turn followed by a hundred; married पुरञ्- jana at his request and lived with him for years together; {{F}}1:  भा. IV. २५. २०-24, ४३-44.{{/F}} felt annoyed at his going for hunting and was consoled by him on his return after which he completely surrendered himself to her; {{F}}2:  Ib. IV. २६. 4 and १३-26.{{/F}} mother of ११०० sons and ११० daughters; {{F}}3:  Ib. IV. २७. 6-7.{{/F}} allegorically she is the बुद्धि or intellect. {{F}}4:  Ib. IV. २९. 5.{{/F}} (See पुरञ्जन).(I)--alias इन्द्रवाह; 