ा. IX. १३. २४.(II)--a son of Citraratha. M. ४८. ९४.(III)--a son Satyavrata. M. १२. ३७. [page३-515+ ३६]--a group of twelve Gods of the Uttama epoch; {{F}}1:  Vi. III. 1. १४.{{/F}} also of तामस. {{F}}2:  Ib. III. 1. १६.{{/F}}--(जयादेवस्) the gods of the epoch of Uttama Manu; twelve in number; {{F}}1:  भा. VIII. 1. २४: Br. II. ३६. २७: III. 4. २९ and ३१८. वा. ६२, २४ and ३७: ६६. 8: ६७. ३७-8.{{/F}} all sons of सत्या and Uttama. These are the यज्ञियस् of the तामस epoch. {{F}}2:  Br. II. ३६. ३६ and ४३.{{/F}}--the father of स्वधाम. भा. VIII. १३. २९.--the अमात्य of Pramati. वा. ५८. ८९.--born of Dharma and सूनृता with the aid of Satyajit, he got rid of the wicked यक्षस्, राक्षसस् and others. भा. VIII. 1. २५-26.(I)--a son of वीतिहोत्र and father of Uru- श्रवस्. भा. IX. 2. २०.(II)--the eldest son of माण्डूकि, (Mar- कण्डेय-वा। प्।) initiated into the portion of the ऋग् Veda left to him by Indrapramati. Br. II. ३४. २९: वा. ६०. २८.--a son of सत्यहिता (tara-वा। प्।); हद् three pupils शाकल्य, Rathitara and बाष्कलि (भरद्वाज); these in their turn hymned separate शाखस्। Br. II. ३४. ३०: वा. ६०. २९-31. [page३-518+ २७]--a son of Satyahita who taught him the ऋग् Samhita1 as he learnt from his father. Va. ६०. २९.--the goddess enshrined at मुकुट. M. १३. ५०.--a son of चाक्षुष Manu. Br. II. ३६. ७९. M. 4. ४१: वा. ६२. ६७ and ९१. [page३-516+ २९]--one of the nine sons of सावर्णि. वा. १००. २१.(I)--a son of Dyumatsena and husband of सावित्री; went to the wood, fell unconscious with head-ache while cutting fuel; the God of Death appeared on the scene; सावित्री noticed him; see सावित्री. M. २०८. १२, २१०.(II)--a son of Manu and नड्वला. Vi. I. १३. 5.--(Satyavat-भा। प्।) a son of Manu चाक्षुष. भा. IV. १३. १६.(I)--a wife of पराशर, and mother of व्यास; {{F}}1:  भा. II. 7. ३६: I. 3. २१: XII. 6. ४९: वा. 1. 2:{{/F}} in her previous birth अच्छोदा the mind-born daugh- ter of the पितृस्; now born as a fisherwoman, of अद्रिका Matsya at the confluence of the गन्गा and the यमुना; {{F}}2:  Br. III. १०. ७३-4: M. १४. १९. वा. ७३. २१-2.{{/F}} her son व्यास, compiled the १८ पुराणस् and the भारत। {{F}}3:  M. ५३. ७०.{{/F}}(II)--(see रूक) a daughter of गाधि and wife of sage ऋचीक. As the चरु intended for her was taken by her mother, she gave birth to an unrighteous son, and on her appeal the sage changed him to an unrighteous grandson. Mother of Jamadagni; she became converted into the river कौशिकी; other sons were शुनक्शेप and शुनह्पुच्छ; {{F}}1:  भा. IX. १५. 5-१२: Br. III. ६६. ३६-59: वा. ६५. ९३: ९१. ६६, ८५, ९२. Vi. IV. 7. १२, ३२, ३३-4.{{/F}} com- pared to दक्षिणा in याग. {{F}}2:  Br. III. 1. ९६: २१. २२.{{/F}}(III)--a daughter of Kratu and daughter-in- law of पर्वश. Br. II. ११. ३८.(IV)--the queen of शन्तनु and mother of विचित्रवीर्य and चित्रान्गद; {{F}}1:  Vi. IV. २०. ३४.{{/F}} at her command कृष्णद्वै- पायन begot धृतराष्ट्र and पाण्डु on the widows of Vici- त्रवीर्य. {{F}}2:  Ib. IV. २०. ३८.{{/F}}(I)--a राजऋषि of द्रविडदेश, born as the son of Vivasvat, the future Vaivasvata Manu; once when he was performing his ablutions a fish fell into his hands. He reared it in a jar and as it grew big it was left in a pond. It grew bigger and was taken to a number of lakes and rivers and finally to the sea. Addressed by the king the fish revealed his true form and warned him against the forth- coming deluge. During the floods Satyavrata, as directed by Matsya Hari, got with the sages, into the ark, creepers and plants and seeds and tied the ship to the horn of the fish. His praise of Hari; heard the मत्स्य पुराण सम्हिता from Hari and after the deluge became Vaivasvata Manu, (s.v.); {{F}}1:  भा. VIII. ch. २४ (whole): IX. 1. 2-3.{{/F}} a महात्मा. {{F}}2:  Br. III. ११. ९२.{{/F}}(II)--a son of Tribandhana, celebrated as त्रिशन्कु (s.v.). भा. IX. 7. 5. [page३-517+ २९](III)--a son of त्रय्यारुणि (त्रय्यामुण- म्। प्।) who took to wife Vidarbha's queen; for this un- righteousness he was banished by his father to live with श्वापकस्; when his father went to the forest there was no shower for १२ years when Satyavrata performed austeri- ties and helped the sons and wives of विश्वामित्र in their livelihood; वसिष्ठ was in charge of the kingdom and did not invite him; enraged at this he killed his cow and fed विश्वामित्र's family; विश्वामित्र noticed three departures from dharma and called him त्रिशङ्कु; विश्वामित्र was pleased with his aid and took him to heaven with his earthly body to the wonder of even वसिष्ठ; his wife was Satya- व्रता and son हरिश्चन्द्र. Br. III. ६३, ७७-113: M. १२. ३७: वा. ८८. ७८-117. Vi. IV. 3. २१-4.(I)--a class of people in शाकद्वीप. भा. V. २०. २७.(II)--sons of Dharma. भा. VIII. 1. २५.--is शकुनि. भा. X. ७८. [९५ (V) १६].--the magic car of iron obtained by tapas from शिव by शाल्व; made by Maya fitted with all illusory powers. भा. X. ७६. 1, 3-7; ७८. १३.--when प्रलय went up to the mahar- lokam and when the whole world was overwhelmed by अहम्कार there was a dispute between ब्रह्मा and कृष्ण when out of the latter's chest a light in the shape of a Linga came out. It was drunk by दक्ष son of ब्रह्मा and the result was the birth of सती. The rest of रस became eight- fold, seven substances bringing fortune and salt. M. ६०. 6-१०.--in honour of उमा; to be begun on Vasanta शुक्ल triti1ya1 and continued for a year every त्रितीया when सती married शिव; after purificatory baths, offer prayers to उमा and also to शिव in the midst of the eight सौभाग्यस् by flowers, incense, etc.; at the end a gift of a bed is prescribed; the performer gets desired things and ultimately reaches heaven; he who does it for १२ years, or 7 or 8 lives a happy long life. Madana, Sata- dhanva, कार्तवीर्य, वरुण and Nandi have done this. M. ६०. 1. ४६. [page३-705+ २५]--sugar cane, रसराज, निष्पाव, जाजि, धान्यकम्, गोक्षीरम्, kurumbham and salt. M. ६०. 7-8, २८.--in honour of भवानी. M. १०१. १६.--a son of Vasudeva. M. ४६. २२.--a son of बृहत्श्लोक and the grandson of वामन. भा. VI. १८. 7-8.(I)--a ऋग् Vedic sage who got himself trans- formed into a youthful person and requested king मान्- धात्रि for his daughter's hand; when he was asked to select one from the harem, he went in, when all his fifty daughters wanted to have him as their husband. So he agreed; after enjoying worldly pleasure for long, he felt the urge for मुक्ति and retired to the forest, with his wives following and became a वैखानसभिक्षु; lived with them; father of १५० sons; when the sage was dead, all his wives burnt themselves on his funeral pyre; {{F}}1:  भा. IX. 6. ३८-55; Vi. IV. 2. ६९ to end.{{/F}} before his marriage he was engaged in penance. Once immersed under the waters of the यमुना in contemplation of the Lord, he saw a fish in sexual union and felt a desire for home life; on another occasion he noticed गरुड consuming a fish, and cursed on behalf of [page३-704+ ३०] the sages that गरुड's visit to कालिन्दि would be his death. {{F}}2:  Ib. X. १७. 9-११.{{/F}} Knew the yoga power of Hari. {{F}}3:  Ib. II. 7. ४५.{{/F}}(II)--a pupil of Devamitra. भा. XII. 6. ५६.(III)--a son of सत्या and कृष्ण. Br. III. ७१. २४७.--a daughter of सत्यभामा. Br. III. ७१. २४८.--a sage. M. १९६. २८.--a भार्गवगोत्रकार. M. १९५. २५.--the lightning of the sky, a daughter of विनता. M. 6. ३४.--also called Mitrasaha and कल्माषान्घ्रि; (कल्माषपाद-वा। प्।) son of सुदास; wife of मदयन्ती, [page३-702+ २९] became a राक्षस through वसिष्ठ's curse. Once as he was hunting, he killed a demon. The latter's brother wanted to wreak vengeance on the king and in the guise of a cook, served human flesh to वसिष्ठ. The sage knew this and cursed him to be a demon for १२ years. The king wanted to curse the sage in return but was stopped by his wife. The consecrated waters fell on his feet and blackened them. Wandering in the forest, he saw a Brahman couple engaged in amorous sports. As a demon he seized the Brahman and ate his flesh despite the lady's protest. She cursed the demon to meet with death in the sexual act and joined her husband on his funeral pyre: after १२ years he returned and longed for union with his queen. She refused remembering the curse of the Brahmana lady. So he appointed वसिष्ठ to beget a son on his queen. As the child was seven years in pregnancy, वसिष्ठ hit her stomach with a stone and the child was born. This was अश्मक. भा. IX. 9. १८-39; वा. 1. १७५; ८८. १७६.--a भार्गव gotraka1ra. M. १९५. २२.--a forest in कैलास. भा. IV. 6. २३ and २८.--a भार्गव gotraka1ra. M. १९५. २६.--the second अवतार् of Hari (वाराह). भा. V. 3. 7.--the sacred thread worn by women after their wedlock. It is said that सीता retained this alone when giving away the other jewels as gifts. भा. IX. ११. 4.--a pupil of सूत. वा. ६१. ५६.--a विद्याधरगण. वा. ६९. २९.--a territorial division of शाल्मलिद्वीप. भा. V. २०. 9.(I)--a composer of the साम वेद। Br. II. ३५. ४४.(II)--लक्ष्मण, met his brother राम in the R. कदली. M. २२. ५३.--a त्रयार्षेय. M. १९८. 7.(I)--the town of Soma visited by Arjuna in search of the dead child of the द्वारका Brahman. भा. X. ८९. ४४. [page३-706+ २५](II)--one of the nine divisions of भारत- वर्ष. Br. II. १६. 9; M. ११४. 8; वा. ४५. ७९; Vi. II. 3. 7.(III)--a मुहूर्त of the night. Br. III. 3. ४३; वा. ६६. ४४.(IV)--a son of Purindrasena (आन्ध्र). M. २७३. १०.(V)--Budha, the son of रोहिणी; born in Nai- मिष. वा. 2. 9.--a mind-born mother. M. १७९. १०.(I)--(Sauram उचानम्)--solar measure- ments. Br. II. २१. १३७; वा. ५०. १८८.(II)--सूक्त of the Yajurvedins; to be recited in tank rituals. M. ५८. ३५; ९३. १३२.(III)--a साम। वा. 9. ४८.(IV)--the place of the moon in the मण्- डलम्. वा. ५३. ५९.(I)--a class of sacred fire. भा. IV. 1. ६३. [page३-707+ २९](II)--a class of पितृस् who drink Soma's स्व- ध; deities of ऋतुस् and hence ऋत्वस्; पितृस् born of Soma. Br. II. २३. ३९, ७५; २८. 4, १५, १८, ७०; M. १०२. २०; १२६. ६९; १४१. 4, १३, १६. वा. ५२. ६७; ५६. १३, १६, ६६; Vi. II. १२. १३.--in honour of शिव and केशव. M. १०१. १४.--a भार्गव gotra. वा. ६५. ९६.--divine birds; sisters of अरुण and गरुड. वा. ६९. ६७.--a mind-born mother. M. १७९. १०.--belonging to the आर्षेय Pravara, Angiras. M. १९६. 7. [page३-703+ २९]--an आत्रेय gotraka1ra. M. १९७. 4.(I)--